heir relationships with authors and publishers, the translators also reveal how they have defined the goals and the process of literary translation. Containing original, detailed biographical and bibliographical material, Writing between the Lines offers many new insights into the literary translation process, and the diverse roles of the translator as social agent. The first text on Canadian translators, it makes a major contribution in the areas of literary translation, comparative literature, Canadian literature, and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literature (French)xTranslations into EnglishxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aFrench-Canadian literaturexTranslations into EnglishxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aFrench-Canadian literaturey20th centuryvTranslations into EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench-Canadian literaturey20th centuryxTranslations into EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aLittérature canadienne-françaisexTraductions anglaisesxHistoire et critiquex20e siècle. 0aTraducteursxBiographiesxCanada. 0aTraduction littérairexCanada. 0aTranslating and interpretingzCanada. 0aTranslatorsxBiographyxCanada. 0aTranslatorszCanadavBiography. 4aLanguage Arts & Disciplines: Translation. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Translating & Interpreting.2bisacsh1 aConacher, AgnÈs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEverett, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodbout, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerslake, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoustas, Jane, econ